For one mole of an ideal gas  

V_{m,\text{ideal}} = \dfrac{RT}{P}

Insert T = 250 K, P = 15 atm and R = 0.082057 \,\text{dm}^3\,\text{atm}\,\text{K}^{-1}\,\text{mol}^{-1}:

V_{m,\text{ideal}} = \dfrac{0.082057 \times 250}{15}
                  = 1.37 \,\text{dm}^3\,\text{mol}^{-1}

The real gas occupies a molar volume 12 % smaller:

V_m = V_{m,\text{ideal}}\,(1 - 0.12)
    = 1.37 \times 0.88
    = 1.20 \,\text{dm}^3\,\text{mol}^{-1}

\boxed{1.20} \,\text{dm}^3\,\text{mol}^{-1}

