Step 1 – Express the concentration profile  
For an exponential decay,
c(x)=c₀e^{−kx}

Step 2 – Determine the decay constant k  
c(10 cm)=½ c₀ ⇒ e^{−k(10 cm)}=½  
k=ln 2/0.10 m=0.693147/0.10=6.93147 m^{−1}

Step 3 – Write the chemical-potential gradient  
μ=μ°+RT ln c  
∂μ/∂x = RT ∂(ln c)/∂x = −RTk

Step 4 – Identify the thermodynamic force  
For diffusion the thermodynamic force is taken as the negative gradient of chemical potential:  
F = −∂μ/∂x = RTk

Step 5 – Insert numerical values (T = 25 °C = 298 K)  
R = 8.314 J mol^{−1} K^{−1}  
RT = (8.314)(298) = 2.48 × 10^{3} J mol^{−1}  
F = (2.48 × 10^{3} J mol^{−1})(6.93147 m^{−1})  
F = 1.72 × 10^{4} J mol^{−1} m^{−1}

Since 1 J m^{−1}=1 N, the result is
F = 1.72 × 10^{4} N mol^{−1} = 1.72 × 10^{1} kN mol^{−1}

\boxed{1.72\times 10^{1}} kN mol^{−1}

The de Broglie wavelength λ of a particle is given by  

\[
\lambda=\frac{h}{p},\qquad p=\sqrt{2mK}
\]

where  
h = 6.626\,070 15 × 10^{-34}\,\mathrm{J\,s} (Planck constant)  
m = 9.109 383 7015 × 10^{-31}\,\mathrm{kg} (electron mass)  
K = 100 eV = 100\,(1.602 176 634 × 10^{-19}) J = 1.602 176 634 × 10^{-17}\,\mathrm{J}

1. Momentum of the electron:

\[
p=\sqrt{2mK}
  =\sqrt{2(9.109\,383\,7015\times10^{-31}\,\mathrm{kg})
            (1.602\,176\,634\times10^{-17}\,\mathrm{J})}
  =5.40\times10^{-24}\,\mathrm{kg\,m\,s^{-1}}
\]

2. de Broglie wavelength:

\[
\lambda=\frac{h}{p}
        =\frac{6.626\,070\,15\times10^{-34}\,\mathrm{J\,s}}
               {5.40\times10^{-24}\,\mathrm{kg\,m\,s^{-1}}}
        =1.23\times10^{-10}\,\mathrm{m}
        =0.123\,\mathrm{nm}
\]

\[
\boxed{0.123}\ \text{nm}
\]

