Step 1 – Centre‐field of the X-band experiment  
The resonance field without hyperfine interaction is  

B_0 = \dfrac{h\,\nu}{g_{\text{iso}}\mu_B}

With  
h = 6.62607015\times10^{-34}\,\text{J s}  
\mu_B = 9.2740100783\times10^{-24}\,\text{J T}^{-1}  
\nu = 9.5\;\text{GHz}=9.5\times10^{9}\,\text{Hz}  
g_{\text{iso}} = 2.005

h/\mu_B = 7.1448\times10^{-11}\;\text{T Hz}^{-1}

B_0 = \frac{7.1448\times10^{-11}\times9.5\times10^{9}}{2.005}
     = 0.33853\;\text{T}

Step 2 – Hyperfine shift  
For a nucleus with I = 1/2 the two EPR lines are at  

B_{m_I} = \dfrac{h(\nu - m_I A)}{g_{\text{iso}}\mu_B}\;(m_I = \pm\tfrac12)

The given hyperfine constant is expressed in frequency units:  
A = 280\;\text{MHz}=2.80\times10^{8}\,\text{Hz}

The field separation of the two lines is  

\Delta B = \frac{hA}{g_{\text{iso}}\mu_B}

The shift of each line from B_0 is therefore  

\delta B = \frac{\Delta B}{2} = \frac{hA}{2g_{\text{iso}}\mu_B}
         = \frac{7.1448\times10^{-11}\times2.80\times10^{8}}{2\times2.005}
         = 0.004989\;\text{T}

Step 3 – Higher-field line (m_I = –½)  
B_{\text{high}} = B_0 + \delta B
                = 0.33853\;\text{T} + 0.004989\;\text{T}
                = 0.34352\;\text{T}

Step 4 – Convert to millitesla  
1 T = 1000 mT ⇒ B_{\text{high}} = 343.5 mT

\boxed{343.5} mT

