Let  

N = 3 \times 10^9  (number of base pairs in the haploid genome)  
n = length (in base pairs) of the DNA sequence we seek.  

1. A specific n-bp sequence has probability (1/4)^n of occurring at any given position (four possible bases per position, assumed equiprobable and independent).

2. Along a genome that is much longer than n, there are ≈ N possible starting positions.  
   Expected number of occurrences of that sequence:

   E = N \,(1/4)^n = N / 4^n.

3. For the sequence to appear, on average, exactly once:

   N / 4^n = 1  ⟹  4^n = N.

4. Solve for n:

   n = \dfrac{\ln N}{\ln 4}
     = \dfrac{\ln(3 \times 10^9)}{\ln 4}
     = \dfrac{\ln 3 + 9 \ln 10}{\ln 4}
     ≈ \dfrac{1.099 + 9(2.303)}{1.386}
     ≈ \dfrac{21.822}{1.386}
     ≈ 15.75.

5. Since n must be an integer and the expected count must not exceed 1, we round up to the next whole base pair:

   n = 16.

\boxed{16}\ \text{bp}

For a first-order reaction, transition-state theory gives  

k = (κ k_B T / h) e^{−ΔG^{‡}/RT}

so at the same temperature

k_{\text{cat}}/k_{\text{uncat}} = e^{-(ΔG^{‡}_{\text{cat}}-ΔG^{‡}_{\text{uncat}})/RT}

Hence the decrease in activation free energy brought about by the enzyme is

ΔΔG^{‡} = ΔG^{‡}_{\text{uncat}} - ΔG^{‡}_{\text{cat}} = RT \ln\!\left(\dfrac{k_{\text{cat}}}{k_{\text{uncat}}}\right)

1. Ratio of rate constants  
   k_{\text{cat}}/k_{\text{uncat}} = 14\,\text{s}^{-1} / 1.0\times10^{-15}\,\text{s}^{-1}
                                   = 1.4\times10^{16}

2. Natural logarithm  
   ln(1.4\times10^{16}) = ln 1.4 + 16 ln 10
                        = 0.336 + 16(2.303)
                        = 37.18

3. RT at 25 °C (298 K)  
   RT = (8.314 J mol^{−1} K^{−1})(298 K) = 2.48\times10^{3}\,J mol^{−1}

4. Free-energy difference  
   ΔΔG^{‡} = (2.48\times10^{3}\,J mol^{−1})(37.18)
           ≈ 9.2\times10^{4}\,J mol^{−1}
           ≈ 92 kJ mol^{−1}

\boxed{92} kJ/mol

Overall complex-formation equilibrium  
Cu^{2+} + 4\,NH_{3}  ⇌  [Cu(NH_{3})_{4}]^{2+} , β_{4}=K_{stable}^{\ominus}=2.1\times10^{13}

1. Initial (analytical) concentrations  
[Cu^{2+}]_{0}=0.20\;{\rm mol\,dm^{-3}}  
[NH_{3}]_{0}=1.0\;{\rm mol\,dm^{-3}}

2. Define x = residual [Cu^{2+}] at equilibrium.  
Total copper is conserved, so  

[Cu(NH_{3})_{4}^{2+}] = 0.20 - x

3. Ammonia remaining after complexation  

[NH_{3}] = 1.0 - 4(0.20 - x)=0.20 + 4x

4. Apply the stability constant  

β_{4}= \dfrac{[Cu(NH_{3})_{4}^{2+}]}{[Cu^{2+}][NH_{3}]^{4}}
      =\dfrac{0.20 - x}{x(0.20+4x)^{4}} = 2.1\times10^{13}

5. Because β_{4} is enormous, x ≪ 0.20 and x ≪ 0.20/4; therefore  
0.20 - x ≈ 0.20 , 0.20+4x ≈ 0.20

Insert these approximations:

2.1\times10^{13}= \dfrac{0.20}{x(0.20)^{4}}
               = \dfrac{0.20}{x(0.0016)}
               = \dfrac{0.20}{1.6\times10^{-3}\,x}
               = \dfrac{125}{x}

Solve for x:

x = \dfrac{125}{2.1\times10^{13}} ≈ 5.9\times10^{-12}

Hence the residual concentration of Cu^{2+} is

\boxed{5.9\times10^{-12}} mol dm^{-3}

