The mass of one atom equals the molar mass divided by Avogadro’s number:

m_{atom} = \frac{M_{\text{Au}}}{N_A}
          = \frac{197\ \text{g mol}^{-1}}{6.02 \times 10^{23}\ \text{mol}^{-1}}
          = 3.27 \times 10^{-22}\ \text{g}

\boxed{3.27 \times 10^{-22}} g

Step 1 – convert the molar volume to the volume of one unit cell  
In a face–centred cubic (fcc) lattice there are 4 atoms per unit cell.

V_\text{cell}=4\;\frac{V_\text{molar}}{N_A}
            =4\frac{10.2\;\text{cm}^3\;\text{mol}^{-1}}{6.02214076\times 10^{23}\;\text{mol}^{-1}}
            =6.776\times 10^{-23}\;\text{cm}^3

Step 2 – relate the edge length a to the atomic radius r  
For fcc: the face diagonal equals 4 r, while the face diagonal is a√2, so  
a = 2√2 r  ⇒  r = a/(2√2).

Step 3 – find a from the unit-cell volume  
a = V_\text{cell}^{1/3}= (6.776\times10^{-23}\;\text{cm}^3)^{1/3}=4.07\times10^{-8}\;\text{cm}=4.07\;\text{Å}

Step 4 – calculate the atomic radius  
r = \frac{a}{2\sqrt{2}} = \frac{4.07\;\text{Å}}{2(1.414)} = 1.44\;\text{Å}

\boxed{1.44} Å

